Stuffed with tomes of all shapes and sizes, this bookcase stores a wealth of knowledge.

The Tenets of the Salandran Faith 

The first duty is to heal the sick and the injured. No other duty will ever outweigh the first. Salandrans will heal those in need without hesitation to the best of their abilities whenever asked. They do this as an act of charity and as a gift both to and from the Goddess. The act of healing is an act of worship. 

The second duty is to heal without prejudice or favour. Salandrans heal all who need their aid without regard to who asks or whether their beliefs match our own. On the battlefield it is our duty to aid the wounded on both sides after the battle is over. This holds true for races traditionally regarded as enemies by local people. If a Salandran is asked for aid in a matter regarding the healing arts they are duty bound to answer. 

The third duty is to seek out and research new ways of healing or of preventing illness. This includes the duty to seek out and lay to rest any undead who may cross the healer's path. The undead are unclean. It is the Salandran's duty to cleanse them. 

The fourth duty is to others. The Salandran will strive for perfection of self through duty to others. Acts of charity and assistance granted to those in need are gifts to Salandra and are the source of the gifts which the Goddess grants us in return. 

The final duty is to seek those in need. Outside the Salandran temples, healers are expected to travel the realm seeking those who require their help. A Salandran cannot cure a healthy man. If a town is healthy it is the duty of a Salandran to move on. Seek out the sick and the injured. They may not be able to come to us. We must find them.

Salandra the Healer 

In times long lost, there was good and evil, just like today, just like in the eons to come. There was illness, famine, pain and death. But there were also those who did not give up. There were those who stood up against the vile and foul. There were heroes. 

This is the tale of three such heroes. This is the tale of Salandra the Healer. 

Salandra was born to insignificant parents on an insignificant island in the Trackless Sea. Humans were only starting to inhabit the island of Amia, and were faced with many difficulties. Salandra saw the agony and poverty of the people, and her heart ached. She prayed to the Crying God to ease their pain, and He called for her. 

Salandra, now a priestess of Ilmater, worked hard in the years to come. She forsook a comfortable life and joined with two other women: Morgana, a strong-willed and determined farmer's daughter, and Eysheila, a wayfarer, pure of heart, in search of a purpose. The Merciful Three quickly made a name for themselves in the turmoil of Amia, a land in desperate need of champions of the common folk. They would heal the sick wherever they went, drive back bands of monsters and help villages in any way they could. 

But destiny had more in store for them. A horrible malady was spreading. Nearly a quarter of the population was infected and the victims returned as undead. It was clear to Salandra that she was to act, that this was her calling. Her companions did not hesitate either. They set out to find the source of this famine and vanquish the undead; Salandra with her morningstar, Morgana with mace and crossbow, and Eysheila with her mighty spear. 

With guidance from the higher powers, the Three found and confronted the source of this evil: a powerful priest of Talona. The battle was fierce, but the gods were with the Three. It was Eysheila's spear that pierced this foul man's heart, but too late. The curse had been bestowed upon the lands of Amia. It would take power beyond the reach of anyone on Amia to stop the spell. Yet Salandra walked straight into the dark heart of the pulsing curse, and began to unweave it. Faith alone kept her on her feet. With compassion, devotion and the goodness in her soul, Salandra dissolved the malady of Talona. Once it was done, she closed her eyes and was taken from the cares of the world. 

The Broken God was moved by this act of selflessness and love. He took the body of Salandra and held her in His arms, crying for the loss. As the tears of a god fell upon her forehead, Salandra awoke. Divinity rushed through her, and she ascended. From then on, Salandra the Healer has served Ilmater beyond time and space, as the gentle goddess we know today. 

Later, Salandra appeared to her companions, and spoke: "Friends. Though I have passed from this world, I have not forgotten it. You must make sure it does not forget me, or the work we have done, either. Morgana, strong and warm: Go and build a house in my name. Continue our work, care for the world and be the foundation of my teachings. Eysheila, fearless and wise: Travel the lands near and far, right the wrongs you see, spread my word and do what I ask of you.. Be my long-reaching arm and mouth." 

The women heeded Salandra's commands. Morgana became the first Temple Mother to the church of Salandra, and Eysheila acted on her own, as a travelling Oracle of the Lady in White. The church may face many changes in the eventful centuries to come, but these two pillars of the faith will never cease to exist. They have been dictated by Salandra herself.

The Salandran cleric is likely to find himself on occasion working upon the battlefield. Inventiveness and speed of action are the key elements to survival of both cleric and the wounded in this situation. 
While limb amputation can usually be achieved in the temples with a minimum of risk and with the leisure to accomplish it cleanly and with time to make a neat and painless job of the operation this is not true of the battlefield situation.
This is where the cleric will find use for a good broadsword or battle-axe to perform the surgery. Speed is of the essence here so the cleric should use a darkfire spell upon the blade to seal the wound as the amputation is performed. Evacuation of the survivors to a temple should be achieved as soon afterward as possible.

This surgical textbook is a step-by-step guide to methods of closing wounds.

Lavishly and gruesomely hand-illustrated it contains chapters on various types of stitching, complete with diagrams.

Other chapters cover such subjects as making needles from bone-shards and suitable types of animal sinew for use as stitching material.

More exotic methods are also covered.

'Extract from Chapter XV!'
Inventiveness is sometimes needed and the Salandran cleric should be aware af any useable sources of material in his surroundings.
For example a colony of fire-ants can be utilised to swiftly close a wound. Press the head of an ant against the edges of the wound and allow it to bite. Pinch off the body, leaving the jaws of the ant clamping the wound. Ignore the screams of the patient. He will thank you later.

It was Peridos the Short-Lived who formulated the basic rules for the use of wild herbs in medical applications. His advice was simple. 
If you eat a herb and it kills you then don't eat it again.
His advice stood him in good stead throughout his life until he was eaten by a wild bear whose supply of wild berries he was harvesting.
Nonetheless his advice has merit. Unfamiliar plants may well have healing properties but eating large quantities is unadvisable until such properties are known. Nibbling a corner of a leaf is a safer option than eating a bush to find out what it does.

Long-term Mental Instability.
A Study of Mander.
by
Nightingale.

The almost permanently empty room with Mander's name on the door in the Isolation Wing of this temple is testament to the difficulty in treating his ailment. 
He has so far proved resistant to the daily Cure Disease spells which were first tried in an attempt to cure him.
He is even more resistant to being kept in his padded cell. 
Mander was diagnosed by me as 'Barking Mad' shortly after my arrival in this region. Nothing I have seen since causes me to doubt this diagnosis. Nothing that has been tried has effected anything remotely close to a cure but perseverance will surely be effective someday.
Salandran clerics encountering Mander in the wild are instructed to cast Cure Disease and Clarity on him if the opportunity arises. The expected reaction from Mander should be the exclamation, "Spoon!" and possibly the summoning of one or more chickens.
This indicates failure and he should be gently encouraged to return to his padded cell.
It will be necessary to try more radical methods of treatment if the Cure spells don't show some effect soon. I have noted the odd effect that lightning strikes have on the senses of those struck. I feel that an experiment may be worthwhile.

Most citizens of the realms are familiar with the Major Gods of the pantheon. Temples to those with the largest numbers of followers, such as Torm, Lathander or Ilmater are familiar sights in many cities.
There are many Lesser Gods too. One of these is Salandra the Healer. The Goddess Salandra is a Handmaiden of Sung the White. Those who have seen the Goddess describe her as a beautiful woman clad in white, who emanates an aura of light and who is surrounded by a feeling of harmony and well-being.
Salandra's  followers are few in number but highly skilled in the arts of healing and of curing disease. Salandran temples are rarely found in large cities. They are most likely to be found in high mountainous regions, or in remote sunlit valleys. The locations are usually chosen to take advantage of beneficial airs or local mineral water sources or other naturally occuring sources of healing. 
On rare occasions the Goddess herself has been known to appear to mortals. All reported occurences of this have been associated with great works of healing. Although these occurences are rare it is said that all clerics who perform acts of healing have the Goddess Salandra at their shoulder while they work. 
Those who dedicate their lives to the healing arts can be sure that the Goddess Salandra will smile upon their efforts.

No spell is more useful to the Salandran surgeon than the simple Sleep spell. Learned by the most junior of clerics it is a gift of the Goddess which permits the performance of surgery without pain to the patient.
It should be noted however that although clerics learn this spell early in their training it is more advisable for a very senior cleric to cast the spell in cases where the surgery is likely to take more than a few minutes. 
It must also be noted that certain people are extremely resistant to the spell. Preparation of spells to sap the will may prove helpful in allowing a subsequent Sleep spell to take effect.
 
If all else fails ask the patient to chew Pipe Herbs. Thereafter a Salandran Hammer applied skilfully to the back of the head is guaranteed to anaesthetise even the sturdiest of patients.

The first duty is to heal the sick and the injured. No other duty will ever outweigh the first. Salandrans will heal those in need without hesitation to the best of their abilities whenever asked. On the battlefield it is our duty to aid the wounded on both sides after the battle is over. This holds true for races traditionally regarded as enemies by local people. If a Salandran is asked for aid in a matter regarding the healing arts they are duty bound to answer.

Seek out the sick and the injured. They may not be able to come to us. We must find them.

The undead are unclean. 
The Salandran cleric will be well aware of the threat posed to the common population by Undead creatures.
Almost without exception the undead are carriers of a wide variety of illnesses and pestilence. They should be destroyed without hesitation wherever encountered and areas of undead infestation should be rigorously cleansed. 
It is the duty of all Salandrans to seek out and destroy all such areas of undead activity. 
The Goddess is generous in the abilities granted to her faithful followers in this respect. Few mortals are more effective in destroying undead than Healing Clerics. The spells granted to healers to aid the injured are also extremely potent when used as combat spells against undead. Spells of Heal and Mass-Heal are strongly recommended as a permanent part of the Salandran's arsenal.

(The inside back cover of this tome has a hand-written note upon it) 

It should be noted that certain local townships permit certain 'trusted' undead to walk freely among them. These poor souls are to be pitied and should be encouraged to visit the temple for free healing.
